I think you want to use [`@BeforeClass`][2] instead of [`@Before`][1]. [`@Before`][1] gets run before each method annotated with [`@Test`][3], whereas [`@BeforeClass`][2] only runs once before all [`@Test`][3] methods.

  [1]: http://junit.sourceforge.net/javadoc/org/junit/Before.html &quot;Before&quot;
  [2]: http://junit.sourceforge.net/javadoc/org/junit/BeforeClass.html &quot;BeforeClass&quot;
  [3]: http://junit.sourceforge.net/javadoc/org/junit/Test.html &quot;Test&quot;

This generation of changeset using `liquibase-hibernate5` does not include the field type changes. If you can see into the `changeset` file you will not find the `changeset` generated regarding your field type change. It seems to be not supported by the `liquibase-hibernate5` plugin.
    
    
 1. Have a look at the comments in this [class][1]
    
    
 2. The developer of this plugin is discussing about it at [link][2]
    
    &gt; The reason these tend to be ignored is because how hibernate
    &gt; represents the datatype is usually different than how the database
    &gt; represents the datatype even when they are actually the same. I&#39;m
    &gt; looking at ways to improve this with Liquibase 4.
    
    
 3. Solution for now would be to add the `diff` manually. The following code is taken from [link][3]
    
        
        &lt;changeSet author=&quot;liquibase-docs&quot; id=&quot;modifyDataType-example&quot;&gt;
            &lt;modifyDataType catalogName=&quot;cat&quot;
                    columnName=&quot;id&quot;
                    newDataType=&quot;int&quot;
                    schemaName=&quot;public&quot;
                    tableName=&quot;person&quot;/&gt;
        &lt;/changeSet&gt;

  [1]: https://github.com/liquibase/liquibase-hibernate/blob/master/src/main/java/liquibase/ext/hibernate/diff/ChangedColumnChangeGenerator.java
  [2]: https://github.com/liquibase/liquibase-hibernate/issues/48#issuecomment-238380616
  [3]: https://www.liquibase.org/documentation/changes/modify_data_type.html

you can just add ChangeSet to your xml file ( in case you&#39;are using xml and not yaml or another file type).

    &lt;changeSet id=&quot;change type&quot; author=&quot;me&quot;&gt;
        &lt;modifyDataType tableName=&quot;Country&quot; columnName=&quot;name&quot; 
               newDataType=&quot;VARCHAR(255)&quot;/&gt;
    &lt;/changeSet&gt; 

For more like adding , renaming and dropping column you can view this link :
